> solved by Roundgod (1:23)

One can see the contribution of the operation of the third type is only related to the number of attacks in the following moves, and the contribution of the operation of the second type is related to the sum of positions of the following attacks. Therefore one may design the following dynamic programming states: $dp[i][j][k]$ denotes we are currently at position $i$, there are $j$ attacks to go, and the sum of their positions is $k$. Calculate the $dp$ backwards, the overall time complexity is $O(n^{4})$.

